# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agar-plate
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] The **Ziehl–Neelsen stain**, also known as the **acid-fast stain**, is a bacteriological staining technique used in cytopathology and microbiology to identify acid-fast bacteria under microscopy, particularly members of the *Mycobacterium* genus.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] This staining method was initially introduced by Paul Ehrlich (1854–1915) and subsequently modified by the German bacteriologists Franz Ziehl (1859–1926) and Friedrich Neelsen (1854–1898) during the late 19th century.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] These acid-fast bacteria possess a waxy lipid-rich outer layer that contains high concentrations of mycolic acid, rendering them resistant to conventional staining techniques like the Gram stain.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] After the Ziehl–Neelsen staining procedure using carbol fuchsin, acid-fast bacteria are observable as vivid red or pink rods set against a blue or green background, depending on the specific counterstain used, such as methylene blue or malachite green, respectively.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Non-acid-fast bacteria and other cellular structures will be colored by the counterstain, allowing for clear differentiation.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] A typical AFB stain procedure involves dropping the cells in suspension onto a slide, then air drying the liquid and heat fixing the cells.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] "Acid alcohol" refers to an alcohol (reagent/solvent-grade; often denatured for tax reasons) solution of hydrochloric acid.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] The percentage refers to the acid content by volume.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] The mechanism of action of the Ziehl–Neelsen stain has long been discussed and is not completely understood.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Historically, it was believed to involve a chemical reaction between the acidic dyes and the cell walls of the bacteria.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] The acidity of the dyes was thought to cause them to bind strongly to the lipid-rich cell walls—particularly to mycolic acids—resulting in the selective staining of only those cells that possess a thick, waxy envelope.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] This traditional view held that these cell-wall lipids were responsible for the retention of the primary dye after acid–alcohol decolourisation, explaining the “acid-fast” property of mycobacteria and related organisms.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] The Ziehl–Neelsen stain is a two-step staining process.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] In the first step, the tissue is stained with a basic fuchsin solution, which stains all cells pink.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] In the second step, the tissue is incubated in an acid-alcohol solution, which decolourises all cells except for acid-fast cells, which retain the colour and appear red.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] The mechanisms by which this colour is produced were historically thought to involve an interaction of basic fuchsin with cell-wall components, creating a stable dye complex responsible for the observed red coloration.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Recent studies have provided a more detailed and experimentally supported interpretation of this process, however alternative hypotheses to the structures stained, including nucleic acids were proposed.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Fluorescence and confocal microscopy show that the primary dyes (carbol fuchsin and auramine O) actually localise to intracellular nucleic acids (DNA and RNA) rather than to the cell wall itself.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] In this updated model, the cell envelope’s role is mainly to prevent the loss of these dyes during acid–alcohol washing, rather than to act as the dye-binding target.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] This intracellular localisation explains the characteristic “beading” pattern observed in Ziehl–Neelsen and fluorescent acid-fast stains, corresponding to the bacterial nucleoids.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Similar nucleic-acid staining patterns are seen in other acid-fast organisms such as *Cryptosporidium*, *Cystoisospora*, and *Schistosoma* spp.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] These findings indicate that acid-fast stains function primarily as nucleic-acid stains whose retention depends on cell-wall integrity rather than direct binding to mycolic acids.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Studies have shown that an AFB stain without a culture has a poor negative predictive value.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] An AFB culture should be performed along with an AFB stain; this has a much higher negative predictive value.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] In anatomic pathology specimens, immunohistochemistry and modifications of Ziehl–Neelsen staining (such as Fite-Faraco staining) have comparable diagnostic utility in identifying *Mycobacterium*.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Both of them are superior to traditional Ziehl–Neelsen stain.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Recent evidence suggests that the low sensitivity of acid-fast stains in histologic sections may be partly due to tissue processing rather than bacterial scarcity.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Standard xylene deparaffinization, routinely used in histopathology, damages the lipid-rich envelope of mycobacteria and markedly reduces fluorescence and detectability with both Ziehl–Neelsen and fluorescent stains.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] A solvent-free, heat-based projected hot-air deparaffinization method significantly increased the yield and fluorescence intensity of mycobacteria in formalin-fixed, paraffin-embedded tissues, without compromising tissue morphology.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] These results indicate that the integrity of the mycobacterial cell wall is essential for acid-fastness and that xylene treatment should be avoided when possible.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Fluorescent Auramine O staining, which targets intracellular nucleic acids, performed better than carbol fuchsin and may represent a superior option for histologic diagnosis of paucibacillary tuberculosis.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Auramine O and Ziehl–Neelsen stains are also useful for detecting intestinal coccidia, particularly *Cryptosporidium*, *Cystoisospora*, and *Cyclospora* species.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] These organisms exhibit partial or full acid-fastness, with oocysts appearing as bright yellow-green (auramine) or pink-red (Ziehl–Neelsen) structures against a contrasting background.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Screening of auramine-stained smears of fecal samples has been shown to markedly improve detection rates of coccidial infections in routine diagnostics, providing a rapid and inexpensive method suitable for large-scale screening programs.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] These findings are consistent with the broader interpretation that acid-fast stains act primarily as nucleic-acid stains whose retention depends on the integrity of the oocyst wall rather than lipid composition.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Ziehl–Neelsen staining is considered a narrow-spectrum fungal stain.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] In other words, it is selective in what kinds of fungi it stains, so it can help differentiate and identify fungi.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] The results of Ziehl–Neelsen staining are variable because many fungal cell walls are not acid-fast.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] An example of a common type of acid-fast fungus that is usually stained with Ziehl–Neelsen staining is *Histoplasma*.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] *Histoplasma* is found in soil and the feces of birds and bats.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Humans can contract histoplasmosis by inhalation of the fungal spores.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] The yeast forms reach the bloodstream and may affect lymph nodes and other organs.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] More recently, acid-fast and fluorescent stains have been shown to highlight structures in the eggs of *Schistosoma* species.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Both Ziehl–Neelsen and auramine O staining demonstrate characteristic fluorescence or chromatic enhancement along the eggshell and within internal structures.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] This has diagnostic relevance, as it may assist in the recognition of eggs in stool and urine samples, particularly in low-intensity infections or after partial degradation.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Fluorescent staining with auramine O has been proposed as a rapid adjunct technique for screening schistosomiasis in endemic regions and differentiating species based on distinct staining patterns.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Earlier work had also demonstrated that Ziehl–Neelsen staining can highlight both the shell and species-specific internal features of schistosome eggs, supporting its diagnostic and taxonomic value.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] These findings, together with fluorescence studies on other acid-fast organisms, further support the interpretation that acid-fast stains primarily target nucleic acids and can reveal diagnostically relevant structures beyond bacteria.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] In 1882 Robert Koch discovered the etiology of tuberculosis.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Soon after Koch's discovery, Paul Ehrlich developed a stain for mycobacterium tuberculosis, called the alum hematoxylin stain.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Franz Ziehl then altered Ehrlich's staining technique by using carbolic acid as the mordant.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Friedrich Neelsen kept Ziehl's choice of mordant but changed the primary stain to carbol fuchsin.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Ziehl and Neelsen's modifications together have developed the Ziehl–Neelsen stain.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] Another acid-fast stain was developed by Joseph Kinyoun by using the Ziehl–Neelsen staining technique but removing the heating step from the procedure.
[src:agar-plate/acid-fast-stain] This new stain from Kinyoun was named the Kinyoun stain.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] The **Actinomycetota** (previously known as **"Actinobacteria"**) are a diverse phylum of Gram-positive bacteria with high guanine-cytosine content (GC content or G+C content).
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] They are of great importance to land flora because of their contributions to soil systems.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] In soil, they help decompose organic matter of dead organisms so the molecules can be taken up anew by plants.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] While this role is also played by fungi, actinomycetota are much smaller and likely do not occupy the same ecological niche.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] In this role, the colonies often grow extensive mycelia, as fungi do, and the name of an important order of the phylum, Actinomycetales (the actinomycetes), reflects that they were long believed to be fungi.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Some soil actinomycetota (such as *Frankia*) live symbiotically with the plants whose roots pervade the soil, fixing nitrogen for the plants in exchange for access to some of the plant's saccharides.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Other species, such as many members of the genus *Mycobacterium*, are important pathogens.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Beyond the great interest in Actinomycetota for their soil role, much is yet to be learned about them.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Although currently understood primarily as soil bacteria, they might be more abundant in fresh waters.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota is one of the dominant bacterial phyla and contains one of the largest of bacterial genera: *Streptomyces*.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] *Streptomyces* and other actinomycetota are major contributors to biological buffering of soils.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] They are also the source of many antibiotics.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Bacteria of the Actinomycetota genus *Bifidobacterium* are the most common in the microbiome of human infants.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Although adults have fewer bifidobacteria, intestinal bifidobacteria help maintain the mucosal barrier and reduce lipopolysaccharides in the intestine.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Although some of the largest and most complex bacterial cells belong to the Actinomycetota, the group of marine Actinomarinales has been described as possessing the smallest free-living prokaryotic cells.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Some Siberian or Antarctic biofilms of these bacteria are said to have the longest lifespan of any organism on Earth, frozen in permafrost at around half a million years ago.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Most actinomycetota of medical or economic significance are in class Actinomycetia, and belong to the order Actinomycetales.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] While many of these cause disease in humans, *Streptomyces* is notable as a source of antibiotics.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Of those actinomycetota not in the Actinomycetales, *Gardnerella* is one of the most researched.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Classification of *Gardnerella* is controversial, and MeSH catalogues it as both a Gram-positive and Gram-negative organism.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota-derived antibiotics that are important in medicine include aminoglycosides, anthracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, tetracyclines, etc.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota have high guanine and cytosine content in their DNA.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] The GC content of actinomycetota can be as high as 70%, though some may have a low GC content.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] Analysis of glutamine synthetase sequence has been suggested for phylogenetic analysis of the Actinomycetota.
[src:agar-plate/actinomycetota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] An **agar plate** is a Petri dish that contains a growth medium solidified with agar, used to culture microorganisms.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Sometimes selective compounds are added to influence growth, such as antibiotics.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Individual microorganisms placed on the plate will grow into individual colonies, each a clone genetically identical to the individual ancestor organism (except for the low, unavoidable rate of mutation).
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Thus, the plate can be used either to estimate the concentration of organisms in a liquid culture or a suitable dilution of that culture using a colony counter, or to generate genetically pure cultures from a mixed culture of genetically different organisms.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Several methods are available to plate out cells.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] In this technique, a drop of the culture on the end of a thin, sterile loop of wire, sometimes known as an inoculator, is streaked across the surface of the agar leaving organisms behind, a higher number at the beginning of the streak and a lower number at the end.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] At some point during a successful "streak", the number of organisms deposited will be such that distinct individual colonies will grow in that area which may be removed for further culturing, using another sterile loop.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Another way of plating organisms, next to streaking, on agar plates is the spot analysis.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] This type of analysis is often used to check the viability of cells and is performed with pinners (often also called froggers).
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] A third technique is using sterile glass beads to plate out cells.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] In this technique, cells are grown in a liquid culture, in which a small volume is pipetted on the agar plate and then spread out with the beads.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Replica plating is another technique used to plate out cells on agar plates.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] These four techniques are the most common, but others are also possible.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] It is crucial to work in a sterile manner to prevent contamination on the agar plates.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Plating is thus often done in a laminar flow cabinet or on the working bench next to a bunsen burner.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] In 1881, Fanny Hesse, who was working as a technician for her husband Walther Hesse in the laboratory of Robert Koch, suggested agar as an effective setting agent, since it had been commonplace in jam making for some time.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Agar plates may be formulated as either permissive, with the intent of allowing the growth of whatever organisms are present, or restrictive or selective, with the intent of only allowing the growth of a particular subset of those organisms.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] This correlates to some degree with defined and undefined media; undefined media, made from natural products and containing an unknown combination of very many organic molecules, is typically more permissive in terms of supplying the needs of a wider variety of organisms.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] In contrast, defined media can be precisely tailored to select organisms with specific properties.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Agar plates may also be indicator plates, in which the organisms are not selected based on growth, but are instead distinguished by a color change in some colonies, typically caused by the action of an enzyme on some compound added to the medium.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] The plates are incubated for 12 hours up to several days, depending on the test that is performed.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Blood agar plates (BAPs) contain mammalian blood (usually sheep or horse), typically at a 5–10% concentration.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] BAPs are enriched, and differential media is used to isolate fastidious organisms and detect hemolytic activity. β-Hemolytic activity will show lysis and complete digestion of red blood cell contents surrounding a colony.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Examples include *Streptococcus haemolyticus*. α-Hemolysis will only cause partial lysis of the red blood cells (the cell membrane is left intact) and appear green or brown due to the conversion of hemoglobin to methemoglobin.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] An example of this would be *Streptococcus viridans*. γ-Hemolysis (or non-hemolytic) is the term referring to a lack of hemolytic activity.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] BAPs also contain meat extract or yeast extract, tryptone, sodium chloride, and agar.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Chocolate agar is a type of blood agar plate in which the blood cells have been lysed by heating the cells to 80 °C.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] It is used for growing fastidious respiratory bacteria, such as *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Chocolate agar is named for its color, and no chocolate is contained in the plate.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Thayer–Martin agar is a chocolate agar designed to isolate *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* and *Neisseria meningitidis*.
[src:agar-plate/agar-plate] Thiosulfate–citrate–bile salts–sucrose agar enhances growth of *Vibrio* spp., including *Vibrio cholerae*.
[src:agar-plate/agar] As found in nature, agar is a mixture of two components, the linear polysaccharide agarose and a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules called agaropectin.
[src:agar-plate/agar] It forms the supporting structure in the cell walls of certain species of algae, and is released on boiling.
[src:agar-plate/agar] The processing of food-grade agar removes the agaropectin, and the commercial product is essentially pure agarose.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar has been used as an ingredient in desserts throughout Asia and also as a solid substrate to contain culture media for microbiological work.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar can be used as a laxative; an appetite suppressant; a vegan substitute for gelatin; a thickener for soups; in fruit preserves, ice cream, and other desserts; as a clarifying agent in brewing; and for sizing paper and fabrics.
[src:agar-plate/agar] The word *agar* comes from **agar-agar**, the Malay name for red algae (*Gigartina*, *Eucheuma*, *Gracilaria*) from which the jelly is produced.
[src:agar-plate/agar] It is also known as **kanten** (Japanese: 寒天) (from the phrase ***kan**-zarashi tokoro**ten*** (寒晒し心太) or "cold-exposed agar"), **Japanese isinglass**, **China grass**, **Ceylon moss**, and **Jaffna moss**.
[src:agar-plate/agar] *Gracilaria edulis* or its synonym *G. lichenoides* is specifically referred to as **agal-agal** or **Ceylon agar**.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Macroalgae have been used widely as food by coastal cultures, especially in Southeast Asia.
[src:agar-plate/agar] In the Philippines, *Gracilaria*, known as *gulaman* (also *guraman*, *gar-garao*, or *gulaman dagat*, among other names) in Tagalog, have been harvested and used as food for centuries, eaten both fresh or sun-dried and turned into jellies.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Carrageenan, derived from gusô (*Eucheuma* spp.), which also congeals into a gel-like texture is also used similarly among the Visayan peoples and have been recorded in the even earlier *Diccionario De La Lengua Bisaya, Hiligueina y Haraia de la isla de Panay y Sugbu y para las demas islas* (c.
[src:agar-plate/agar] 1637) of the Augustinian missionary Alonso de Méntrida (in Spanish).
[src:agar-plate/agar] In the book, Méntrida describes gusô as being cooked until it melts, and then allowed to congeal into a sour dish.
[src:agar-plate/agar] In Ambon Island in the Maluku Islands of Indonesia, agar is extracted from *Graciliaria* and eaten as a type of pickle or a sauce.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Jelly seaweeds were also favoured and foraged by Malay communities living on the coasts of the Riau Archipelago and Singapore in Southeast Asia for centuries.
[src:agar-plate/agar] 19th century records indicate that dried *Graciliaria* were one of the bulk exports of British Malaya to China.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Poultices made from agar were also used for swollen knee joints and sores in Johore and Singapore.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar normally solidifies at room temperature without the need to freeze.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar was first subjected to chemical analysis in 1859 by the French chemist Anselme Payen, who had obtained agar from the marine algae *Gelidium corneum*.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Beginning in the late 19th century, agar began to be used as a solid medium for growing various microbes.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar was first described for use in microbiology in 1882 by the German microbiologist Walther Hesse, an assistant working in Robert Koch's laboratory, on the suggestion of his wife Fanny Hesse.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar quickly supplanted gelatin as the base of microbiological media, due to its higher melting temperature, allowing microbes to be grown at higher temperatures without the media liquefying.
[src:agar-plate/agar] With its newfound use in microbiology, agar production quickly increased.
[src:agar-plate/agar] This production centered on Japan, which produced most of the world's agar until World War II.
[src:agar-plate/agar] However, with the outbreak of World War II, many nations were forced to establish domestic agar industries in order to continue microbiological research.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Around the time of World War II, approximately 2,500 tons of agar were produced annually.
[src:agar-plate/agar] By the mid-1970s, production worldwide had increased dramatically to approximately 10,000 tons each year.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Since then, production of agar has fluctuated due to unstable and sometimes over-utilized seaweed populations.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar consists of a mixture of two polysaccharides: agarose and agaropectin.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agarose constitutes about 70% of the mixture, while agaropectin constitutes about 30% of it.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agarose is a linear polymer made up of repeating units of agarobiose, a disaccharide made up of D-galactose and 3,6-anhydro-L-galactopyranose.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agaropectin is a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules that occur in lesser amounts, and is made up of alternating units of D-galactose and L-galactose heavily modified with acidic side-groups, such as sulfate, glucuronate, and pyruvate.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar exhibits a phenomenon known as hysteresis whereby, when mixed with water, it solidifies and forms a gel below about 32–42 °C (305–315 K; 90–108 °F), which is called the gel point, and melts above 85 °C (358 K; 185 °F), which is the melting point.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Hysteresis is the property of having a difference between the gel point and melting point temperatures.
[src:agar-plate/agar] This property lends a suitable balance between easy melting and good gel stability at relatively high temperatures.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Since many scientific applications require incubation at temperatures close to human body temperature (37 °C), agar is more appropriate than other solidifying agents that melt at this temperature, such as gelatin.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar-agar is a natural vegetable gelatin counterpart.
[src:agar-plate/agar] It is white and semi-translucent when sold in packages as washed and dried strips or in powdered form.
[src:agar-plate/agar] It can be used to make jellies, puddings, and custards.
[src:agar-plate/agar] When making jelly, it is boiled in water until the solids dissolve.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Sweetener, flavoring, coloring, fruits and or vegetables are then added, and the liquid is poured into molds to be served as desserts and vegetable aspics or incorporated with other desserts such as a layer of jelly in a cake.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar-agar is approximately 80% dietary fiber, so it can serve as an intestinal regulator.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Its bulking quality has been behind fad diets in Asia, for example the *kanten* (the Japanese word for agar-agar) diet.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Once ingested, *kanten* triples in size and absorbs water.
[src:agar-plate/agar] This results in the consumers feeling fuller.
[src:agar-plate/agar] One use of agar in Japanese cuisine is in *anmitsu*, a dessert made of small cubes of agar jelly and served in a bowl with various fruits or other ingredients.
[src:agar-plate/agar] It is also the main ingredient in *mizu yōkan*, another popular Japanese food.
[src:agar-plate/agar] In Philippine cuisine, it is used to make the jelly bars in the various gulaman refreshments like *sago't gulaman*, *samalamig*, or desserts such as *buko pandan*, *agar flan*, *halo-halo*, *fruit cocktail jelly*, and the black and red *gulaman* used in various fruit salads.
[src:agar-plate/agar] In Vietnamese cuisine, jellies made of flavored layers of agar-agar, called *thạch*, are a popular dessert, and are often made in ornate molds for special occasions.
[src:agar-plate/agar] In Indian cuisine, agar is used for making desserts.
[src:agar-plate/agar] In Burmese cuisine, a sweet jelly known as *kyauk kyaw* is made from agar.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar jelly is widely used in Taiwanese bubble tea.
[src:agar-plate/agar] It can be used as addition to (or as a replacement for) pectin in jelly, jam, or marmalade, as a substitute to gelatin for its superior gelling properties, and as a strengthening ingredient in souffles and custards.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Another use of agar-agar is in a Russian dish *ptich'ye moloko* (bird's milk), a rich jellified custard (or soft meringue) used as a cake filling or chocolate-glazed as individual sweets.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar-agar may also be used as the gelling agent in gel clarification, a culinary technique used to clarify stocks, sauces, and other liquids.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Mexico has traditional candies made out of Agar gelatin, most of them in colorful, half-circle shapes that resemble a melon or watermelon fruit slice, and commonly covered with sugar.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar-agar is an allowed nonorganic/nonsynthetic additive used as a thickener, gelling agent, texturizer, moisturizer, emulsifier, flavor enhancer, and absorbent in certified organic foods.
[src:agar-plate/agar] An agar plate or Petri dish is used to provide a growth medium using a mix of agar and other nutrients in which microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, can be cultured and observed under the microscope.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar is indigestible for many organisms so that microbial growth does not affect the gel used and it remains stable.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar is typically sold commercially as a powder that can be mixed with water and prepared similarly to gelatin before use as a growth medium.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Nutrients are typically added to meet the nutritional needs of the microbes organism, the formulations of which may be "undefined" where the precise composition is unknown, or "defined" where the exact chemical composition is known.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar is often dispensed using a sterile media dispenser.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Different algae produce various types of agar.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Each agar has unique properties that suit different purposes.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Because of the agarose component, the agar solidifies.
[src:agar-plate/agar] When heated, agarose has the potential to melt and then solidify.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Because of this property, they are referred to as "physical gels".
[src:agar-plate/agar] In contrast, polyacrylamide polymerization is an irreversible process, and the resulting products are known as chemical gels.
[src:agar-plate/agar] There are a variety of different types of agar that support the growth of different microorganisms.
[src:agar-plate/agar] A nutrient agar may be permissive, allowing for the cultivation of any non-fastidious microorganisms; a commonly used nutrient agar for bacteria is the Luria Bertani (LB) agar which contains lysogeny broth, a nutrient-rich medium used for bacterial growth.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Additionally, 2216 Marine Broth (MB) agar, with high salt content, is optimized for growing heterotrophic marine bacteria like those of the *Vibrio* genus, while Terrific Broth (TB) agar is used to non-selectively culture high yields of the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:agar-plate/agar] More generally, enriched media is an agar variety that is infused with the necessary nutrients required by fastidious organisms to grow.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Despite the large diversity of agar mediums, yeast extract is a common ingredient across all varieties as it is a macronutrient that provides a nitrogen source for all bacterial cell types.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Other fastidious organisms may require the addition of different biological fluids such as horse or sheep blood, serum, egg yolk, and so on.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Agar plates can also be selective, and can be used to promote the growth of bacteria of interest while inhibiting others.
[src:agar-plate/agar] A variety of chemicals may be added to create an environment favourable for specific types of bacteria or bacteria with certain properties, but not conducive for growth of others.
[src:agar-plate/agar] For example, antibiotics may be added in cloning experiments whereby bacteria with antibiotic-resistant plasmid are selected.
[src:agar-plate/agar] In addition to antibiotic treated agar, other selective and indicator agar plates include TCBS agar and MacConkey agar.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Thiosulfate citrate bile salts sucrose (TCBS) agar is used to differentiate Vibrio species based on their sucrose metabolism, since only some will metabolize the sucrose in the plate and change its pH.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Indicator dyes included in the gel will display a visual change of the pH by changing the gel color from green to yellow.
[src:agar-plate/agar] MacConkey agar contains bile salts and crystal violet to selectively grow gram-negative bacteria and differentiate between species using pH-indicator dyes that demonstrate lactose metabolism properties.
[src:agar-plate/agar] As a gel, an agar or agarose medium is porous and therefore can be used to measure microorganism motility and mobility.
[src:agar-plate/agar] The gel's porosity is directly related to the concentration of agarose in the medium, so various levels of effective viscosity (from the cell's "point of view") can be selected, depending on the experimental objectives.
[src:agar-plate/agar] A common identification assay involves culturing a sample of the organism deep within a block of nutrient agar.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Cells will attempt to grow within the gel structure.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Motile species will be able to migrate, albeit slowly, throughout the gel, and infiltration rates can then be visualized, whereas non-motile species will show growth only along the now-empty path introduced by the invasive initial sample deposition.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Another setup commonly used for measuring chemotaxis and chemokinesis utilizes the under-agarose cell migration assay, whereby a layer of agarose gel is placed between a cell population and a chemoattractant.
[src:agar-plate/agar] As a concentration gradient develops from the diffusion of the chemoattractant into the gel, various cell populations requiring different stimulation levels to migrate can then be visualized over time using microphotography as they tunnel upward through the gel against gravity along the gradient.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Research grade agar is used extensively in plant biology as it is optionally supplemented with a nutrient and/or vitamin mixture that allows for seedling germination in Petri dishes under sterile conditions (given that the seeds are sterilized as well).
[src:agar-plate/agar] Nutrient and/or vitamin supplementation for *Arabidopsis thaliana* is standard across most experimental conditions.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Murashige & Skoog (MS) nutrient mix and Gamborg's B5 vitamin mix in general are used.
[src:agar-plate/agar] A 1.0% agar/0.44% MS+vitamin dH2O solution is suitable for growth media between normal growth temps.
[src:agar-plate/agar] When using agar, within any growth medium, it is important to know that the solidification of the agar is pH-dependent.
[src:agar-plate/agar] The optimal range for solidification is between 5.4 and 5.7.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Usually, the application of potassium hydroxide is needed to increase the pH to this range.
[src:agar-plate/agar] A general guideline is about 600 μl 0.1M KOH per 250 ml GM.
[src:agar-plate/agar] This entire mixture can be sterilized using the liquid cycle of an autoclave.
[src:agar-plate/agar] This hormone/GM solution can be spread across the surface of Petri dishes sown with germinated and/or etiolated seedlings.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Experiments with the moss *Physcomitrella patens*, however, have shown that choice of the gelling agent – agar or Gelrite – does influence phytohormone sensitivity of the plant cell culture.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Gelidium agar is used primarily for bacteriological plates.
[src:agar-plate/agar] Gracilaria agar is used mainly in food applications.
[src:agar-plate/agar] In 2016, AMAM, a Japanese company, developed a prototype for agar-based commercial packaging system called Agar Plasticity, intended as a replacement for oil-based plastic packaging.
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] 'Bacterium actinomycetem comitans' was first described by Klinger (1912) as coccobacillary bacteria isolated with *Actinomyces* from actinomycotic lesions in humans.
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] It was reclassified as *Actinobacillus actinomycetemcomitans* by Topley & Wilson (1929) and as *Haemophilus actinomycetemcomitans* by Potts *et al.* (1985).
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] The species has attracted attention because of its association with localized aggressive periodontitis.
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] Recent studies have shown a phylogenetic similarity of *A. actinomycetemcomitans* and *Haemophilus aphrophilus*, *H. paraphrophilus*, and *H. segnis*, suggesting the new genus *Aggregatibacter* for them.
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] It is one of the bacteria that might be implicated in destructive periodontal disease.
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] Although it has been found more frequently in localized aggressive periodontitis, prevalence in any population is rather high.
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] It has also been isolated from actinomycotic lesions (mixed infection with certain *Actinomyces* species, in particular *A. israelii*).
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] It possesses certain virulence factors that enable it to invade tissues, such as the pore-forming toxin leukotoxin A.
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] It has also been isolated from women with bacterial vaginosis and as an etiologic agent in endocarditis.
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] The pore-forming toxin LtxA of *A. actinomycetemcomitans* may be a trigger of the autoimmune disease rheumatoid arthritis due to its ability to stimulate protein citrullination, a post-translational protein modification targeted by autoantibodies in this disease.
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] In bacteria, small RNAs are involved in gene regulation.
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] Jorth et al. identified 9 sRNA by Northern blotting from computer-predicted candidates in strain VT1169 and 202 sRNA by RNA seq in strain 624.
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] A systematic screen by RNA-seq and RT-PCR in HK1651 strain (a clinical isolate from an aggressive periodontitis patient), quantified 70 sRNAs and further identified 17 differentially expressed sRNAs during growth phases.
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] Target prediction indicated possibility of sRNA interaction with several virulence genes.
[src:agar-plate/aggregatibacter-actinomycetemcomitans] This study confirmed the presence of one of previously identified Fur regulated sRNAs JA04 identified in strain HK1651.
[src:agar-plate/alcohol-burner] An **alcohol burner** or **spirit lamp** is a piece of laboratory equipment used to produce an open flame.
[src:agar-plate/alcohol-burner] It can be made from brass, glass, stainless steel or aluminium.
[src:agar-plate/alcohol-burner] Alcohol burners are preferred for some uses over Bunsen burners for safety purposes, and in laboratories where natural gas is not available.
[src:agar-plate/alcohol-burner] Their flame is limited to approximately 5 centimeters (two inches) in height, with a comparatively lower temperature than the gas flame of the Bunsen burner.
[src:agar-plate/alcohol-burner] While they do not produce flames as hot as other types of burners, they are sufficiently hot for performing some chemistries, standard microbiology laboratory procedures, and can be used for flame sterilization of other laboratory equipment.
[src:agar-plate/alcohol-burner] A small alcohol burner is also preferred for camping when the need for fire is modest.
[src:agar-plate/alcohol-burner] It burns the alcohol vapor that rises due to the heat from the flame through the holes on the top perimeter of the container.
[src:agar-plate/alcohol-burner] Typical fuel is denatured alcohol, methanol, or isopropanol.
[src:agar-plate/alcohol-burner] A cap is used as a snuffer for extinguishing the flame.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] A **crocodile clip** or **alligator clip** is a plier-like spring-tensioned metal clip with elongated, serrated jaws that is used for creating a temporary electrical connection.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] This simple mechanical device gets its name from the resemblance of its jaws to those of a crocodile or alligator.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] It is used to clamp and grab onto a bare wire or a lead on a battery or some other electrical component.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] The clip's tapered, serrated jaws are forced together by a spring to grip an object.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] A Kelvin clip is a special form of crocodile clip whose jaws are insulated from each other, allowing two isolated wires to connect to a single test point.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] This enables 4-wire measurement of circuits with very low resistances.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] The clip is typically covered by a plastic shroud or "boot" to prevent accidental short-circuits.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] Small versions, ranging in size from 15–40 mm (0.59–1.57 in) in length, are used in electrical laboratory work.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] Large versions of these clips, called **automotive clips** or **battery clamps**, are made of solid copper for low electrical resistance, and are used with thick insulated copper cables to make connections between automobile batteries.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] 'jump leads') are capable of delivering hundreds of amperes of current needed to directly power an automobile starter motor, or to transfer energy from a charged lead–acid battery to a discharged one.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] The alligator clip was first introduced to the founder of the Mueller Electric Company, the primary producer of crocodile clips, by John H.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] It was introduced as a wire with a lightbulb in the middle, with a clip on either end of the wire.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] The clip was intended for use by electricians, and would allow them to easily tap into a live wire to power a portable light.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] The clip was mostly covered by rubber tubing as insulation.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] Several metal clip designs working on the same principle were patented in the early 20th century.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] A type of a crocodile clip cutting through the wire insulation was patented by Harry Frankel from New York in 1903, and another design was developed by Westinghouse Electric Corporation engineer George Brown Dusinberre, who patented it in 1909, and later was hired by Ralph S.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] Mueller & Co. to refine the design, with a later version patented in 1921.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] Dusinberre's redesign was significantly cheaper than Williams' initial design.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] While Mueller approved of the design, Williams was strongly opposed to any changes to the original design.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] While Dusinberre offered to write Mueller as the co-inventor for his improved design while filing the patent, Mueller declined as he believed it was not his idea.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] The first models produced by Muller and Dusinberre's partnership, R.S.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] Mueller & Company, were steel coated with zinc.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] This combination of metals was easily soiled, so zinc was swapped out for nickel plating.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] The success of the crocodile clips is largely credited to Charles Kettering's invention of the electric self-starter for motor vehicles.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] As automobile manufacturers began using this technology initially intended for Cadillacs, a need was produced for something that could connect batteries in storage to a charger.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] Mueller produced a larger version, for automobiles, of the crocodile clips referred to commonly as jumper cables and a smaller version for motorcycles.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] Dusinberre eventually lost interest in the company and allowed Mueller to buy out his shares for $52,300.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] The company was renamed Mueller Electric.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] The United States Defense Logistics Agency specifies several types of electrical clips in Commercial Item Description (CID) A-A-59466.
[src:agar-plate/alligator-clip] In this CID document, crocodile clips are designated type CC, alligator clips are designated types TCx, and other types of electrical clips have various other, unique designations.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] The Alphaproteobacteria are a diverse taxon and comprise several phototrophic genera, several genera metabolising C1-compounds (e.g.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] *Methylobacterium* spp.), symbionts of plants (e.g.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] *Rhizobium* spp.), endosymbionts of arthropods (*Wolbachia*) and intracellular pathogens (e.g.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] Moreover, the class is sister to the protomitochondrion, the bacterium that was engulfed by the eukaryotic ancestor and gave rise to the mitochondria, which are organelles in eukaryotic cells (see Endosymbiotic theory).
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] A species of technological interest is *Agrobacterium tumefaciens* (also called *Rhizobium radiobacter*): scientists often use this species to transfer foreign DNA into plant genomes.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] Aerobic anoxygenic phototrophic bacteria, such as *Pelagibacter ubique*, are alphaproteobacteria that are a widely distributed and may constitute over 10% of the open ocean microbial community.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] Several points of disagreement muddy the recovery of the phylogenetic relationships among the Alphaproteobacteria clades from the genomic data.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] One such point centers on the placement of the Pelagibacterales stemming from the large differences in gene content (*e.g.* genome streamlining in *Pelagibacter ubique*) and GC-content between members of several orders.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] Specifically, certain species within Pelagibacterales, Rickettsiales, and Holosporales possess AT-rich genomes, containing higher-assayed concentrations of adenine-thymine (AT) pairs than guanine-cytosine (GC) base pairs.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] While it could be a case of convergent evolution resulting in an artefactual clustering, several studies disagree and no consensus has been reached.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] Furthermore, the GC-content of ribosomal RNA, the traditional phylogenetic marker for prokaryotes, does not correlate well with the GC-content of the genome.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] For example, members of the Holosporales have a much higher ribosomal GC-content than members of the Pelagibacterales and Rickettsiales, though they are more closely related to species with high genomic GC-contents than to members of the latter two orders.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] Alphaproteobacteria are divided into three subclasses, Magnetococcidae, Rickettsidae, and Caulobacteridae.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] The basal group is Magnetococcidae, composed of a large diversity of magnetotactic bacteria only one of which, Magnetococcus marinus, is formally described.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] The Rickettsidae is composed of the intracellular Rickettsiales and the free-living Pelagibacterales.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] The Caulobacteridae is composed of the Holosporales, Rhodospirillales, Sphingomonadales, Rhodobacterales, Caulobacterales, Kiloniellales, Kordiimonadales, Parvularculales, and Sneathiellales.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] Comparative analyses of the sequenced genomes have revealed many conserved insertion-deletions (indels) in widely distributed proteins and whole proteins (i.e. signature proteins) that are distinctive characteristics of either all Alphaproteobacteria, or their different main orders (viz.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] Rhizobiales, Rhodobacterales, Rhodospirillales, Rickettsiales, Sphingomonadales and Caulobacterales) and families (viz.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] Rickettsiaceae, Anaplasmataceae, Rhodospirillaceae, Acetobacteraceae, Bradyrhiozobiaceae, Brucellaceae and Bartonellaceae).
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] These molecular signatures provide a means to circumscribe the taxonomic groups and to identify and assign new species accurately.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] Phylogenetic analyses and conserved indels in large numbers of other proteins provide evidence that Alphaproteobacteria have branched off later than most other phyla and classes of Bacteria except Betaproteobacteria and Gammaproteobacteria.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] Other phylogenetic debates turn on the placement of Magnetococcidae and the protomitochondrion.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] There are some debates for the inclusion of Magnetococcidae in Alphaproteobacteria.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] For example, an independent proteobacterial class ("*Candidatus* Etaproteobacteria") for Magnetococcidae has been proposed.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] A recent phylogenomic study suggests the placement of the protomitochondrial clade between Magnetococcidae and all other alphaproteobacterial taxa, which suggests an early divergence of the protomitochondrial lineage from the rest of alphaproteobacteria, except for Magnetococcidae.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] This phylogeny also suggests that the protomitochondrial lineage does not necessarily have a close relationship to Rickettsidae.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN).
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] The phylogeny is based on whole-genome analysis.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] Subclass names are based on Ferla *et al*.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] Although only a few studies have been reported on natural genetic transformation in the Alphaproteobacteria, this process has been described in *Agrobacterium tumefaciens*, *Methylobacterium organophilum*, and *Bradyrhizobium japonicum*.
[src:agar-plate/alphaproteobacteria] Natural genetic transformation is a sexual process involving DNA transfer from one bacterial cell to another through the intervening medium, and the integration of the donor sequence into the recipient genome by homologous recombination.
